1.4  Five-Year Accident History 



N/A - This is a new facility. There is no data to report.  



1.5  The Emergency Response Program



The Emergency Response Program is divided into two elements, as only properly trained and qualified personnel are authorized to respond to emergencies.  CF employees & contracted production workers are trained to notify and evacuate via the Plant's Emergency Action Plan.  The MCAS & City of Yuma Fire Departments would respond to an emergency; support would be made available via WPS personnel trained to 29 CFR 1910.120(q) standards.  Appropriate written plans are maintained on-site and updated on a regular basis.  Local Emergency Response capabilities have been verified.



1.6   Planned changes to improve safety



The primary mechanisms to identify and plan safety improvements include (but are not limited to):

?    Daily rounds;

?    Process Hazard Analysis revalidation/update;

?    Compliance Audits;

?    Routine inspections & maintenance (Mechanical Integrity Program);

?    Triennial IIAR Bulletin 109 Inspections;



Each of the Programs above may result in recommendations ranging from capital improvements to routine maintenance of the plant.  Work Orders are established in parallel to identified needs.  Recent planned changes to improve safety include:



?    Implementation of recent PHA recommendations



Implementation of these measures has commenced according to the schedule set by the management of CF, LLC.
